<subSubSection id="C32DF8BD965AFFF3FF2711C33AE0FCB5" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B88AB36965AFFF3FF2711C3387AFCF7" blockId="3.[178,1086,419,792]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">
Description: Length: 
<quantity id="4CCF06D3965AFFF3FE6511C33B3FFE57" box="[496,560,419,440]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.0" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788" unit="mm" value="8.0">8 mm</quantity>
; length of fore-body: 
<quantity id="4CCF06D3965AFFF3FC8C11C33A64FE57" box="[793,875,419,440]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.1" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788" unit="mm" value="4.1">4.1 mm</quantity>
. Body black, shiny; mouthparts, antennae and legs testaceous (fore-body 
<figureCitation id="130CB7B3965AFFF3FD4C11A03A16FE39" box="[729,793,448,470]" captionStart="Figs 3-4" captionStartId="11.[178,218,1497,1519]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,238,1434]" captionTargetId="figure-80@11.[178,1085,212,1463]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 3-4: Fore-body (fb), head (h), aedoeagus in lateral view (al), aedoeagus in ventral view (av), male sternite VII (s7), male sternite VIII of: 3: P. cuccodoroi; 4: P. duplopunctata Fig. 3: P. cuccodoroi 3fb 3al 3av Fig. 4: P. duplopunctata 4fb 4h 4al 4av" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5873562" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5873562/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
). Head transverse (1 x 1.2), the eyes very large and prominent, the temples short with well marked postero-lateral angles (
<figureCitation id="130CB7B3965AFFF3FE96119B385DFDFE" box="[259,338,507,529]" captionStart="Figs 3-4" captionStartId="11.[178,218,1497,1519]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,238,1434]" captionTargetId="figure-80@11.[178,1085,212,1463]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 3-4: Fore-body (fb), head (h), aedoeagus in lateral view (al), aedoeagus in ventral view (av), male sternite VII (s7), male sternite VIII of: 3: P. cuccodoroi; 4: P. duplopunctata Fig. 3: P. cuccodoroi 3fb 3al 3av Fig. 4: P. duplopunctata 4fb 4h 4al 4av" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5873562" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5873562/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">Fig. 4h</figureCitation>
); surface with numerous irregularly scattered large and small punctures leaving a narrow impunctate area on vertex and two other broader ones posteriorly. Pronotum as long as broad (
<quantity id="4CCF06D3965AFFF3FE6012553B40FDA4" box="[501,591,565,587]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.3" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788" unit="mm" value="1.3">1.3 mm</quantity>
). widest at anterior 1/3 
<superScript id="7C42067E965AFFF3FCC0124F3A6DFDD2" attach="none" box="[853,866,559,573]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">rd</superScript>
, the sides retracted posteriorly, the postero-lateral angles broadly rounded; discal series of 6 large irregularly spaced punctures. Elytra sub-quadrate, as long as broad (
<quantity id="4CCF06D3965AFFF3FD6D12103A44FD6A" box="[760,843,624,645]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.4" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788" unit="mm" value="1.4">1.4 mm</quantity>
); each elytron with five series of numerous, closely spaced punctures, the interstriae with a few randomly disposed other punctures; the interstria beween series IV and V, and sides just beyond series V with numerous much smaller punctures, albeit larger than the small punctures of pronotum, the interstices devoid of microsculpture. Abdominal tergites with sparse small asperate punctures.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B88AB36965AFFF3FF2713473AE0FCB5" blockId="3.[178,1085,807,859]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">
Male: sternite VII unmodified; emargination of sternite VIII shaped like those of related species, extending to about 6/16 
<superScript id="7C42067E965AFFF3FE62135E3B05FCA3" attach="left" box="[503,522,830,844]" fontSize="6" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">ths</superScript>
the length of sternite; aedoeagus: 
<figureCitation id="130CB7B3965AFFF3FCF313253AA9FCB4" box="[870,934,837,859]" captionStart="Figs 3-4" captionStartId="11.[178,218,1497,1519]" captionTargetBox="[178,1085,238,1434]" captionTargetId="figure-80@11.[178,1085,212,1463]" captionTargetPageId="11" captionText="Figs 3-4: Fore-body (fb), head (h), aedoeagus in lateral view (al), aedoeagus in ventral view (av), male sternite VII (s7), male sternite VIII of: 3: P. cuccodoroi; 4: P. duplopunctata Fig. 3: P. cuccodoroi 3fb 3al 3av Fig. 4: P. duplopunctata 4fb 4h 4al 4av" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5873562" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5873562/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">Figs 4</figureCitation>
al, 4av.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C32DF8BD965AFFF3FF27130A3813FC55" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B88AB36965AFFF3FF27130A3813FC55" blockId="3.[178,1085,874,954]" pageId="3" pageNumber="1788">This new species is very distinctive among members of the Nigerrima group due to the dense double puncturation of fore-body, with relatively large diameter of the secondary punctures.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
